 others' financial precarity; why the increasing role of animals and children in contemporary art points to the turn away from paid labor; and how the expansion of MFA programs and student debt helps create the conditions for decommodified labor. In showing how socially engaged art operates within and against the need to be paid for work, La Berge offers a new theorization of the relationship between art and contemporary capitalism.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Sep 2020) 0aArt and social action. 0aArt and society. 0aArtxEconomic aspects. 0aArtxStudy and teachingxSocial aspects. 0aArtists and community. 0aArtistsxPolitical activityxHistoryy21st century. 0aSocial practice (Art) 0aSocial practice (Art). 7aART / Criticism.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK eBook-Package 2019z978311069632540uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781478005278zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781478005278423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781478005278.jpg  a978-3-11-069632-5  DUK eBook-Package 2019b2019  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles